So she's leaving.

41:34.915 --> 41:39.359
She's marrying Richard Landon, the head of the Fisher Rivers Library in Toronto.

41:40.040 --> 41:42.382
Book people stick together, don't they?

41:42.422 --> 41:43.544
So she's moving to Canada.

41:43.964 --> 41:47.407
She's moving to Canada at the end of this month.

41:47.427 --> 41:48.048
I'll stick with me, Penny.

41:48.068 --> 41:49.469
She's only 35 miles away.

41:49.509 --> 41:50.771
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

41:50.791 --> 41:51.912
She'll be easier to try.

41:52.012 --> 41:56.536
She'll have her mind more on books, including books in boxes.

41:56.677 --> 41:58.558
Now, let's talk generally.

41:58.578 --> 42:04.264
Here we have two young, capable, talented, highly

42:04.733 --> 42:15.564
trained, and did have much spoken, young women, and this must be an unusual kind of assignment.

42:16.565 --> 42:19.288
You came from Texas to the Rosenbach.

42:19.328 --> 42:21.791
How many volumes do we have here, roughly?

42:21.811 --> 42:23.532
20,000 volumes.

42:23.552 --> 42:29.098
Roughly, that's a small collection, right?

42:29.118 --> 42:29.759
27,000 volumes.

42:30.019 --> 42:31.681
And last week I was in the University of Chicago.

42:31.701 --> 42:31.821
Right.

42:33.455 --> 42:36.199
I mean, there's something great about having a small collection.

42:36.259 --> 42:40.164
I'm looking for statements like that.

42:40.484 --> 42:48.615
I mean, you know, I can say that I have handled just about everything in this collection, physically.

42:48.635 --> 42:54.242
And certainly you could never say that about being lived at Texas or the University of Chicago.

42:54.263 --> 42:55.704
I mean, it's just impossible.

42:56.245 --> 43:02.213
And the longer you're here, the more you are able to understand about it, because it is a

43:02.598 --> 43:14.897
Because it is small, and you can take on a project and know that you can actually finish it, because it's not at some, you know, tremendously large institution where everything catalogs seems like a hopeless plan.

43:14.917 --> 43:23.731
Okay, having handled everything, virtually everything, do you feel that you understand the focus, the scheme of the collection?

43:23.891 --> 43:28.318
Oh, I think it's very easy to understand the focus of the collection, the collector's collection.

43:28.771 --> 43:30.333
Well, is it a Highspot collection?

43:30.353 --> 43:37.562
It's a Highspot collection, with the exception that I mentioned before when I was talking about us as a research library.

43:38.944 --> 43:41.147
And that... Yeah, but I don't think he had that in mind.

43:41.407 --> 43:48.396
Well, you have to understand that the Rosenbach collection is not just Dr. Rosenbach's collection.

43:48.497 --> 43:56.567
In fact, very little of it was ever Dr. Rosenbach's own personal collection.

43:57.509 --> 44:08.662
Dr. Rosenbach died, and then Phillips died a year later, the trustees selected from Rosenbach Company's stock what they wanted to go into what was then the Rosenbach Foundation.

44:09.283 --> 44:22.939
And so to say that a particular book was part of Dr. Rosenbach's collection, I mean, I know how to find that, but I think until a few years ago, the distinctions were not very apparent even to people who worked here.

44:23.760 --> 44:26.503
And also, Dr. Rosenbach had others.

44:26.821 --> 44:36.817
The books that were here, that were his, you know, close to his, really close to his art kind of books, were Americana books.

44:36.837 --> 44:45.291
And his other special personal collecting interests, like the children's books, he gave to the free library.

44:45.631 --> 44:46.893
And he's Judaica.

44:46.913 --> 44:49.918
I mean, he... Was it a Judaica?

44:49.938 --> 44:52.022
The American Jewish Historical Society.

44:52.042 --> 44:52.482
That's right.

44:52.502 --> 44:54.145
He sold a silent trench.

44:54.445 --> 45:00.901
Yes, another Rosenbach story, in which we were involved, because we were the only people who had... Tell me, tell me, tell me.

45:00.921 --> 45:02.686
I'm starting a chapter with that.

45:02.706 --> 45:03.287
Oh, my gosh.

45:03.327 --> 45:05.553
We need to talk to Peter Solis-Cohen as well.

45:05.573 --> 45:06.736
I don't know if you've talked ahead.

45:06.856 --> 45:07.518
I know Lita.

45:08.480 --> 45:11.307
Peter is Lita's nephew-in-law.

45:11.405 --> 45:15.130
He took the Solacellas name, but he was not a Solacellas name.

45:15.150 --> 45:15.991
She told me that.

45:16.291 --> 45:18.994
Oh, they all take great names.

45:19.014 --> 45:21.317
You know, he's not really a Solacellas.

45:21.377 --> 45:29.167
He's the one who kind of took on the historical authority about all of this, because some Solace Cohen family stuff had been told as well.

45:29.187 --> 45:34.273
Well, there's an interesting... I mean, the guy bought this thing with the express idea that he hated it.

45:34.794 --> 45:35.715
That's right.

45:35.735 --> 45:38.539
And that's the justification.

45:38.579 --> 45:39.640
That's why I'm looking at this.

45:40.058 --> 45:41.921
This really kind of opens up the whole area.

45:42.221 --> 46:02.514
Who collects the unspeakable things, the Holocaust stuff, the Ku Klux Klan stuff, as horrible as it is in order to not, you know, somebody has to keep it to preserve it, because one of my pieces is the collector is more than an accumulator, a true collector, preserves stuff, you know, at some point.

46:02.654 --> 46:05.138
Well, Rosenwald had Rosenbach purchase it.

46:05.405 --> 46:06.626
with that in mind.

46:06.646 --> 46:12.893
He also said that's the only time I ever told the doctor that price is no object.

46:13.114 --> 46:13.394
Buy it.

46:13.414 --> 46:16.057
Well, he only had to pay 4K for it.

46:16.077 --> 46:18.240
But, you know, he never said that with the Gutenberg Bible.

46:18.680 --> 46:21.443
He must have had a price how high he was willing to go.

46:21.483 --> 46:22.665
It was an auction.

46:22.685 --> 46:24.326
It was an auction in Europe.

46:24.366 --> 46:27.430
But he said he wanted it, and then he did not want it to go into the wrong hands.

46:29.412 --> 46:30.834
He didn't even want to keep it for himself.

46:31.314 --> 46:32.676
No, he didn't want anything.

46:33.457 --> 46:34.618
But why did he buy it?

46:35.341 --> 46:38.885
Well, to keep it out of the hands of the Nazis.

46:38.985 --> 46:42.109
It's an interesting collecting story, isn't it?

46:42.129 --> 46:46.174
And I think he just wanted it to be seen in context.

46:46.874 --> 46:51.860
And that's why it went not into his own personal collection, but to the Jewish Historical Society.

46:51.980 --> 46:54.003
That's the best yet.

46:54.023 --> 47:01.051
Where it won't be kind of plucked out and held up as this anti-Semitic text.

47:01.191 --> 47:01.872
Which it was.

47:02.071 --> 47:09.166
Which it was, but it could be viewed in the context of all of this other... We're talking about the murder of children here.

47:09.287 --> 47:12.574
Ritual murder, you know, of child names.

47:12.594 --> 47:21.092
We needed two sentences out of this to... But given those times, you know, this was just all... Listen, we've got a story up in Boston about the guy who...

47:21.376 --> 47:22.678
Oh, yeah.

47:22.698 --> 47:23.659
It's not just Boston.

47:23.679 --> 47:28.285
Well, I mean, the whole white community went berserk over this as, well, they should, you know.

47:29.747 --> 47:30.729
But these things happen.

47:30.749 --> 47:35.575
But I think that... How did you become involved in this thing before we generalize?

47:35.936 --> 47:36.697
Oh, God.

47:37.378 --> 47:42.245
Well, everyone was trying to find out.

47:43.646 --> 47:49.915
I mean, from... My understanding is that the American Jewish Historical Society

47:50.249 --> 47:55.878
didn't even really know how it came to be there, or what the reason was that they had it.

47:56.699 --> 48:01.727
They knew that they had to wait until a certain date, and then they sold it.

48:03.409 --> 48:04.611
And they didn't even wait that long.

48:04.852 --> 48:07.636
They didn't, well, it was close, I mean, a few weeks.

48:08.037 --> 48:12.223
And Lessing Rosenwald

48:12.625 --> 48:15.829
writes about it in his reminiscences of a collector.

48:15.869 --> 48:17.251
I cannot find that book.

48:17.431 --> 48:18.372
Well, it's right over there.

48:18.653 --> 48:21.256
Can you at least show me what the book looks like?

48:21.276 --> 48:23.239
Sure.

48:23.299 --> 48:24.861
It's black and a slip stitch.

48:24.881 --> 48:29.567
That is a very difficult book to find.

48:31.489 --> 48:40.641
There is material in the files about this.

48:41.532 --> 48:47.059
Did he actually, was he correct that he gave the doctor a, this has never been read, do you know that?

48:47.279 --> 48:47.940
No, it wouldn't have to.

48:48.120 --> 48:48.541
I've read it.

48:48.561 --> 48:53.147
Look at it, it's, it's... We wash our hands.

48:54.829 --> 48:56.271
It's a beautifully done book.

48:57.011 --> 48:58.593
There's not a whole lot of content to it.

48:58.694 --> 49:00.916
I mean, you don't really go to it to find out.

49:01.838 --> 49:03.159
It's not that old a book.

49:03.660 --> 49:05.722
Why cannot I find a copy of this?

49:05.742 --> 49:08.586
It's very, I mean, it was privately distributed.

49:08.819 --> 49:14.165
And when you've got any grandchildren at Blessing Reginald, that's a big part of the press run, I think.

49:14.185 --> 49:20.973
I'm surprised that nobody... Chincintown.

49:21.534 --> 49:22.275
Elberthorpe.

49:22.775 --> 49:31.585
That was the name of the gallery, and the Elberthorpe Gallery was where the art and the books were passed.

49:31.605 --> 49:32.787
What was the limitation of this?

49:32.827 --> 49:37.132
Do we know offhand?

49:37.232 --> 49:38.353
250 copies.

49:40.004 --> 49:42.908
I'm sure the Rosenwald family still has a lot of them.

49:42.928 --> 49:43.889
Wouldn't you think?

49:44.750 --> 49:45.431
I don't know.

49:45.551 --> 49:48.835
I don't know how they distributed them.

49:48.855 --> 49:50.297
Where is the Rosenwald family?

49:50.317 --> 49:59.668
Well, Edith, a blessing's widow, died a year ago, two days after Christmas.

50:00.349 --> 50:08.139
And her son, Julius Dooley Rosenwald, is the executor of the estate.

50:08.159 --> 50:09.741
And there are...

50:09.923 --> 50:20.335
A number of Westingian youth children are still around here, but Dooley is the one that we have the most contact with.

50:20.355 --> 50:30.807
And his son-in-law, Werner Bootsheimer, is the director of the Folger Shakespeare Library.

50:30.927 --> 50:36.133
It's almost incestuous as well.

50:36.839 --> 50:40.944
Well, this is, we're going up in directions I never dreamed that we were going to .

50:40.964 --> 50:50.195
Well, we were talking about, you know, what, you know, we're trying to make the collection usable in such a way that it answers questions like this, about book collectors and collections.

50:50.495 --> 50:50.595
Well.

50:50.615 --> 51:02.830
And I think that in some ways, I mean, coming from such a broad collection as Texas, one might think, oh, this is so confining because

51:03.147 --> 51:09.496
You know, it's so much smaller and so much more limited in some way.

51:09.516 --> 51:23.496
But the fact that it is all centered around such a very large image of a man or of these brothers gives it a kind of a cohesion.

51:23.596 --> 51:30.927
And it's not like a small collection put together by two people who didn't matter or that

51:31.109 --> 51:34.012
included materials that only mattered to them.

51:34.493 --> 51:43.623
I mean, how can you be unexcited about the manuscript of Ulysses or the Faison book or, you know, or all these things?

51:43.643 --> 51:47.807
I mean, this is that string of pearls that I've got to do that.

51:47.827 --> 51:49.549
Yeah, give me that quote again.

51:52.392 --> 51:59.580
He denies it, but I told people when I first came here, when they asked me, you know, coming from Texas here,

51:59.982 --> 52:04.387
What's it like my husband said to someone?

52:04.407 --> 52:17.423
At Texas, it was like Ellen was dealing with the whole bottom of the ocean floor, you know, the wrecked ships and sunken treasure and just all kinds of unmined strange fish.

52:17.703 --> 52:21.728
Very strange fish, a few sea monsters and so on.

52:21.948 --> 52:24.912
But at Rosenbach, it's just like a string of pearls.

52:25.753 --> 52:27.795
Perfect pearls, isn't it?

52:27.860 --> 52:28.842
No, no.

52:29.442 --> 52:43.905
And there are some things that have a nicer path than others, but I think that in general... And it's not, to me, it's all so interconnected.

52:43.925 --> 52:50.195
I mean, you call it incestuous, but the world of scholarship is of making connections.

52:50.696 --> 52:52.939
And I can't tell you how often...

52:53.324 --> 53:02.975
I see people here that I knew in Texas, you know, there were search paths, crosses, back and forth, criss-crosses around through all these collections.

53:03.115 --> 53:05.398
Well, I was telling Leslie that it's amazing.

53:05.458 --> 53:13.868
I really know there comes a point where I really have to see somebody when two or three different people mention their names to me.

53:14.809 --> 53:16.911
You know, for instance, this guy at Arizona.

53:18.874 --> 53:21.677
Nicholas Barker came from Worcester at the Antiquarian Society.

53:22.703 --> 53:24.985
He says, you really got to see this guy, Dickinson, in Arizona.

53:25.005 --> 53:26.968
He's doing a biography of Huntington.

53:26.988 --> 53:33.274
So I sit right down to me while I'm calling for ten people a week and talking to them, setting up as many of these scripts as I can.

53:34.235 --> 53:35.657
And now you do it again.

53:35.677 --> 53:37.198
I ask you about Huntington.

53:37.218 --> 53:39.141
He says, oh, this guy, Dickinson.

53:39.161 --> 53:40.222
Is that the guy in Arizona?

53:40.302 --> 53:40.942
I asked you.

53:40.962 --> 53:41.443
He said, yes.

53:41.503 --> 53:42.824
I said, you're the second one.

53:44.206 --> 53:44.967
You know, these names.

53:45.848 --> 53:49.892
Now, this is Nicholas Barker from England telling me about a guy in Arizona who knows

53:50.142 --> 53:51.984
as much as there is to know about Huntington.

53:52.064 --> 53:55.968
Well, and Dickinson is just very much on.

53:55.988 --> 54:02.415
I mean, he really is kind of in the peak of this research and turning over the stones.

54:04.798 --> 54:09.723
I gather there's probably a lot of other people who know a lot about Huntington.

54:09.743 --> 54:13.067
Well, I'm not competitive in any way to what he's doing.

54:13.087 --> 54:16.591
I'm looking, you know, for five or six pages on the guy.

54:16.611 --> 54:19.474
But something that would really profile him

54:20.180 --> 54:24.726
other than what you get from the Huntington Library.

54:24.746 --> 54:25.366
It's wonderful.

54:25.567 --> 54:28.851
I saw one quote in a book about his art collecting.

54:29.111 --> 54:33.657
Somebody said, oh God, that he owned every judge and everybody else in California.

54:33.677 --> 54:34.858
Have you ever seen that quote?

54:34.878 --> 54:37.201
No, not surprising.

54:37.221 --> 54:41.646
I mean, the guy, what he didn't have, he bought.

54:41.666 --> 54:43.148
And he married his uncle's wife.

54:43.168 --> 54:45.411
And he married his uncle's wife.

54:45.931 --> 54:47.553
Did he know his books?

54:47.813 --> 54:50.456
Again, to go back, I think that came in context.

54:50.597 --> 54:53.140
I asked if he... Whether he was an accumulator or a collector.

54:53.160 --> 54:54.121
Or did he know his books?

54:55.823 --> 54:56.664
How could he possibly?

54:56.684 --> 54:59.627
He had a whole staff in New York, even just... Some of them were never unpacked.

54:59.647 --> 55:02.631
Some of them were never even unpacked.

55:02.651 --> 55:06.656
He just wanted to put together a great collection, and that's what counted.

55:08.078 --> 55:12.563
I mean, he did put together a book collection, and he didn't choose, you know.

55:12.998 --> 55:17.883
Well, they probably hired some wonderful people, too, if that helps.

55:18.103 --> 55:26.572
Well, Huntington, before Dr. Rosenbach, had his agent, George D. Smith, I'm not sure if the name was one of the four.

55:26.972 --> 55:36.202
And really, if Smith had not died when he did, the question of whether Rosenbach would have become the dealer that he became... That's in the book, but I mentioned that to Edwin this morning.

55:36.222 --> 55:37.403
I said you'd point out that

55:37.957 --> 55:43.643
One of the luckiest things to happen to the doctor's career was that Smith died when he did.

55:44.564 --> 55:45.646
He has a letter in the book.

55:45.926 --> 55:46.767
I forget who he wrote.

55:47.508 --> 55:48.949
You know, I would like to be your dealer now.

55:49.410 --> 55:53.835
You know, I'm sure I'll... We'll be happy to execute any of your questions.

55:53.855 --> 55:57.299
And I'm sure that they jumped on the band right now.

55:57.499 --> 55:58.941
At some point, I want to talk about Texas.

56:01.123 --> 56:04.547
I hear your arrival may be anticipated.

56:06.369 --> 56:07.390
What do you hear?

56:08.045 --> 56:09.972
I don't know if this is really...

